---
export const prerender = true;
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";

const ARTICLE_JSON_LD = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  headline: "Switching from Smithery to Rhumb: When It Makes Sense (and When It Doesn't)",
  datePublished: "2026-03-21T00:00:00Z",
  author: { "@type": "Person", name: "Pedro Nunes" },
  description:
    "An honest comparison between Smithery and Rhumb for AI agent tool discovery. When Rhumb is the better choice, when Smithery is, and how to use both.",
  url: "https://rhumb.dev/blog/switching-from-smithery",
  publisher: { "@type": "Organization", name: "Rhumb", url: "https://rhumb.dev" },
};
---

<Layout
  title="Switching from Smithery to Rhumb"
  description="When Rhumb is the better choice for AI agent tool discovery, when Smithery is, and how to use both together. An honest migration guide."
  canonical="/blog/switching-from-smithery"
  ogTitle="Switching from Smithery to Rhumb — Rhumb"
  ogDescription="Honest comparison: catalog breadth vs. trust depth for AI agents. When to switch, when to stay, and how to use both."
  ogUrl="https://rhumb.dev/blog/switching-from-smithery"
  jsonLd={ARTICLE_JSON_LD}
>
  <div class="bg-navy min-h-screen" data-testid="migration-guide" data-page-type="blog">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-16">
      <header>
        <p class="text-xs font-mono font-semibold text-amber uppercase tracking-widest mb-3">Migration Guide</p>
        <h1 class="font-display font-bold text-3xl sm:text-4xl text-slate-100 leading-tight tracking-tight">
          Switching from Smithery to Rhumb: When It Makes Sense (and When It Doesn't)
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-slate-500">
          March 2026 · 8 min read
        </p>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
          Smithery and Rhumb solve different problems. Smithery is an MCP server registry —
          the largest catalog of agent-accessible tools. Rhumb is a trust and quality layer —
          it scores tools, surfaces failure modes, and executes capabilities with cost controls.
          This guide helps you figure out which one you actually need.
        </p>
      </header>

      <article class="mt-12 prose-invert">
        <!-- The honest comparison -->
        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-6">The honest comparison</h2>

          <div class="overflow-x-auto">
            <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
              <thead>
                <tr class="border-b border-slate-700">
                  <th class="text-left py-3 pr-4 text-slate-500 font-mono text-xs">Dimension</th>
                  <th class="text-left py-3 pr-4 text-slate-500 font-mono text-xs">Smithery</th>
                  <th class="text-left py-3 text-slate-500 font-mono text-xs">Rhumb</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody class="text-slate-300">
                <tr class="border-b border-slate-800/50">
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-slate-400">Catalog size</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-emerald-400">4,000+ MCP servers</td>
                  <td class="py-3">525 services scored</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-slate-800/50">
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-slate-400">Quality scoring</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4">Community ratings</td>
                  <td class="py-3 font-semibold text-emerald-400">20-dimension AN Score with confidence</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-slate-800/50">
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-slate-400">Failure mode docs</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4">None</td>
                  <td class="py-3 font-semibold text-emerald-400">Per-service failure modes</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-slate-800/50">
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-slate-400">Cost estimation</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4">None</td>
                  <td class="py-3 font-semibold text-emerald-400">Pre-execution cost estimates</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-slate-800/50">
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-slate-400">Credential modes</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4">Managed OAuth</td>
                  <td class="py-3 font-semibold text-emerald-400">BYOK + Managed + x402 USDC</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-slate-800/50">
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-slate-400">Agent payments</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4">Stripe only</td>
                  <td class="py-3 font-semibold text-emerald-400">x402 USDC (no account needed)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-slate-800/50">
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-slate-400">Time to first tool</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-emerald-400">Minutes</td>
                  <td class="py-3">Minutes (discovery is free, no auth)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-slate-800/50">
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-slate-400">Onboarding</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-emerald-400">Web UI + CLI</td>
                  <td class="py-3">CLI + API (MCP or REST)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-slate-800/50">
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-slate-400">Pricing (execution)</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4">25,000 free RPCs/mo, then $30/mo</td>
                  <td class="py-3">Cost + 20% margin per call</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4 text-slate-400">Best for</td>
                  <td class="py-3 pr-4">Exploration, breadth, rapid prototyping</td>
                  <td class="py-3">Production reliability, compliance, autonomous agents</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- When to switch -->
        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-6">When Rhumb is the better choice</h2>

          <div class="space-y-6">
            <div class="bg-surface border border-slate-800 rounded-lg p-5">
              <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-emerald-400 mb-2">Your agent picks tools autonomously</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">
                If a human selects which MCP server to use, Smithery's catalog is fine. But if your
                agent is choosing tools at runtime — based on capability, cost, and reliability —
                it needs quality signals. Rhumb's AN Score gives agents a machine-readable trust metric
                that community star ratings can't provide.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface border border-slate-800 rounded-lg p-5">
              <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-emerald-400 mb-2">You need to know how tools fail before they fail</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">
                Rhumb documents failure modes per service: what error codes you'll see, common rate limit
                behaviors, and authentication edge cases. In production, knowing that an API returns 500
                on malformed dates (instead of 400) before you hit it is the difference between a retry
                and a crash loop.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface border border-slate-800 rounded-lg p-5">
              <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-emerald-400 mb-2">You need cost controls</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">
                Rhumb provides pre-execution cost estimates and per-agent budget caps. Your agent knows
                what a call will cost before making it, and can route to cheaper alternatives automatically.
                This matters when an agent is running unattended and could burn through credits.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface border border-slate-800 rounded-lg p-5">
              <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-emerald-400 mb-2">Your agent has its own wallet</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">
                x402 payments let agents pay per-call with USDC on Base. No account signup, no OAuth flow,
                no human in the loop. The payment is the authentication. If your agent operates autonomously
                with its own funds, this is the most native payment path.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface border border-slate-800 rounded-lg p-5">
              <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-emerald-400 mb-2">You need alternatives at runtime</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">
                When a provider goes down, Rhumb surfaces scored alternatives for the same capability.
                Your agent can failover to a backup without human intervention. Smithery lists tools
                but doesn't tell your agent which one to switch to when the first choice fails.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- When to stay -->
        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-6">When Smithery is the better choice</h2>

          <div class="space-y-6">
            <div class="bg-surface border border-slate-800 rounded-lg p-5">
              <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-amber mb-2">You need maximum catalog breadth</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">
                Smithery has 4,000+ MCP servers. Rhumb has 525 scored services. If you're exploring
                what's possible, experimenting with niche tools, or building a proof-of-concept where
                breadth matters more than depth, Smithery is the right starting point.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface border border-slate-800 rounded-lg p-5">
              <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-amber mb-2">A human is selecting the tools</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">
                If a developer manually picks which tools to connect, they can apply their own judgment
                about quality. Smithery's web UI makes browsing and installation fast. The trust layer
                is less critical when human judgment is in the loop.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface border border-slate-800 rounded-lg p-5">
              <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-amber mb-2">You want a web UI for management</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">
                Smithery offers a polished web dashboard for managing servers, viewing analytics, and
                configuring connections. Rhumb is API-first and MCP-first — the web interface is for
                reading scores and comparisons, not for managing tool connections.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface border border-slate-800 rounded-lg p-5">
              <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-amber mb-2">You need hosted MCP servers</h3>
              <p class="text-sm text-slate-400">
                Smithery can host MCP servers for you, handling infrastructure and scaling. Rhumb
                doesn't host tools — it proxies requests to upstream providers. If you need managed
                hosting for custom MCP servers, Smithery is the right choice.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Using both -->
        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-6">Using both together</h2>

          <div class="bg-surface border border-amber/20 rounded-lg p-6">
            <p class="text-sm text-slate-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
              The best setup for many teams: <strong class="text-slate-100">discover on Smithery, deploy through Rhumb.</strong>
            </p>
            <ol class="space-y-3 text-sm text-slate-400">
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="text-amber font-mono font-bold shrink-0">1.</span>
                <span>Browse Smithery's catalog to find tools that match your use case</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="text-amber font-mono font-bold shrink-0">2.</span>
                <span>Check the tool's AN Score on Rhumb — look at execution score, access readiness, and confidence</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="text-amber font-mono font-bold shrink-0">3.</span>
                <span>Read the failure modes on Rhumb before integrating</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="text-amber font-mono font-bold shrink-0">4.</span>
                <span>Route production traffic through Rhumb for cost controls, budget caps, and failover</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="text-amber font-mono font-bold shrink-0">5.</span>
                <span>Keep Smithery for experimenting with new tools outside your production stack</span>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Migration steps -->
        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-6">Migration steps</h2>

          <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 mb-6">
            If you're moving production workloads from Smithery to Rhumb:
          </p>

          <div class="space-y-4">
            <div class="bg-surface border border-slate-800 rounded-lg p-5">
              <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-slate-200 mb-2">1. Check coverage</h3>
              <p class="text-xs text-slate-400">
                Search for your current tools on Rhumb:
              </p>
              <pre class="mt-2 text-xs font-mono text-slate-300 bg-elevated rounded p-3 overflow-x-auto"><code>curl "https://api.rhumb.dev/v1/search?q=your-tool-name"</code></pre>
              <p class="mt-2 text-xs text-slate-500">
                If the tool isn't in Rhumb's catalog yet, you can still use it via BYOK mode
                with your own credentials — Rhumb will proxy the request but won't have scoring data.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface border border-slate-800 rounded-lg p-5">
              <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-slate-200 mb-2">2. Compare credential modes</h3>
              <p class="text-xs text-slate-400">
                Smithery uses managed OAuth. Map your current auth to one of Rhumb's three modes:
              </p>
              <ul class="mt-2 space-y-1 text-xs text-slate-400">
                <li><span class="text-amber">BYOK:</span> Bring your existing API keys. Rhumb adds routing and scoring, you keep billing with the provider. No Rhumb markup.</li>
                <li><span class="text-amber">Managed:</span> Rhumb holds the credentials and bills you. Upstream cost + 20% margin.</li>
                <li><span class="text-amber">x402:</span> Pay per call with USDC. No account needed. 15% margin.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface border border-slate-800 rounded-lg p-5">
              <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-slate-200 mb-2">3. Switch the MCP server</h3>
              <p class="text-xs text-slate-400">
                Replace the Smithery MCP config with Rhumb's:
              </p>
              <pre class="mt-2 text-xs font-mono text-slate-300 bg-elevated rounded p-3 overflow-x-auto"><code>{`// Before (Smithery)
"smithery": {
  "command": "smithery",
  "args": ["mcp", "run"]
}

// After (Rhumb)
"rhumb": {
  "command": "npx",
  "args": ["rhumb-mcp"],
  "env": { "RHUMB_API_KEY": "rhumb_live_..." }
}`}</code></pre>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-surface border border-slate-800 rounded-lg p-5">
              <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-slate-200 mb-2">4. Test with discovery first</h3>
              <p class="text-xs text-slate-400">
                Before switching execution, use Rhumb's read-only endpoints alongside Smithery to verify
                coverage. Discovery endpoints are free and require no authentication.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- What we're honest about -->
        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-6">What we're honest about</h2>

          <div class="bg-surface border border-red-500/20 rounded-lg p-6">
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-slate-400">
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="text-red-400">→</span>
                <span><strong class="text-slate-200">Catalog gap is real.</strong> Smithery has 8x more listings. If a tool exists only on Smithery, that's where you'll find it.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="text-red-400">→</span>
                <span><strong class="text-slate-200">No web UI for tool management.</strong> Rhumb is API-first. If you want a visual dashboard for connecting tools, Smithery is more polished.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="text-red-400">→</span>
                <span><strong class="text-slate-200">No hosted MCP servers.</strong> Rhumb proxies to upstream providers. It doesn't host custom MCP servers for you.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex gap-3">
                <span class="text-red-400">→</span>
                <span><strong class="text-slate-200">Per-call pricing can add up.</strong> Smithery's flat $30/month is simpler to budget. Rhumb's per-call model is transparent but harder to predict upfront.</span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Bottom line -->
        <section class="border-t border-slate-800 pt-8">
          <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-slate-100 mb-4">Bottom line</h2>
          <p class="text-slate-400 leading-relaxed">
            Smithery is the best place to discover MCP tools. Rhumb is the best place to evaluate
            and deploy them. If your agent browses a catalog with human guidance, Smithery is great.
            If your agent picks tools autonomously, manages its own budget, and needs to know
            how things fail before they fail, Rhumb is built for that.
          </p>
          <div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap gap-4 text-sm">
            <a href="/quickstart" class="text-amber hover:underline">Quickstart →</a>
            <a href="/search" class="text-amber hover:underline">Search services →</a>
            <a href="/compare" class="text-amber hover:underline">Comparisons →</a>
            <a href="/docs/failure-modes" class="text-amber hover:underline">Failure modes →</a>
          </div>
        </section>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
